So many people buy retics when they’re small and then dump them at rescues and zoos when they get too big. Zoos and rescues aren’t capable of caring for thousands of retics, so a lot of them end up euthanized.
I don’t think people realize that the majority of retics bought as pets, end up euthanized before they reach their full size. Stop buying giant snakes if you can’t house them for their whole lives.

It’s also important to remember that wild snakes get much more exercise than captive snakes do, so they don’t need nearly as much food in captivity. Many people feed their snakes every week, or even twice a week but for many species, this is unnecessary

This is also why variety is important! Rats that we feed in captivity are often very fatty. A variety of feeders like rats, mice, chicks, quails, etc. Can all help your snake maintain a healthy weight/size https://t.co/7QUAsFAlig

Some snakes even continue to gain weight/grow during long fasts. Obese, power fed snakes have unfortunately become so normalized in the pet trade, that many don’t even know what a healthy one looks like anymore.
A few of my ball pythons, like angel here are about 4 years old and are only now approaching full size. Again, these snakes shouldn’t be ready to breed by age 1 or 2 🥴 https://t.co/o8URfknByO

Wild rainbow boas grow SO slow. Likely due to their slower metabolisms and cooler temp preferences. Many wild rainbow boas don’t don’t reach sexual maturity until around 8 years old! https://t.co/T0qdAMYu5d
This is Marvin, he’s over 3 years old and just over 4 feet. Due to boas slow metabolisms Marvin only gets fed 1-2 times per month max. Marvins body composition is amazing https://t.co/a1NAFZuwUK

Most adult pythons/boa should not be full grown by 2 years. Boas especially as they have slower metabolisms. many wild boas don’t reach adulthood until 5-8 years old. Lean, slower growing snakes are ideal. Let’s stop normalizing power feeding and obesity in snakes!!

@BreezExotics Right!? We keep hundreds of species in lizards in captivity, almost all of them get kept on loose substrate but for some reason beardies and Leo’s will die
Calcium sand clumps together when wet, which is why this can be an issue. This substrate However, softens and falls apart when wet. It does not harden.

People also asked “what if the substrate hardens inside of them” it’s not going to do this. In order to harden, the substrate needs to be wet, and then exposed to air and dried out.  If ingested, it’s not going to be exposed to air so it will not harden inside your animal.

A lot of people were worried about the stone desert substrate I used because it “looked” like sand. You can’t judge something purely off what it resembles. While it may “appear” like sand, it’s a natural clay soil. The two are very different.

If your animal is being care for properly, substrate is going to easily pass through. But if their care in incorrect (ex: not enough heat) their digestive system can be compromised, and this is when you start to have issues pop up.

And if your animal does happen to ingest substrate, as long as you’re care is correct, it’s not going to be an issue. Reptiles rely on things like proper nutrition, proper supplements, correct temperatures, etc. To stay healthy, and keep their digestive track functioning!

First off, these animals are far more intelligent than we give them credit for. They know the difference between dirt, and food. I’ve never once seen one of my animals get substrate in their mouth, and not attempt to spit it out. You don’t have to worry so much!

Loose substrate is perfectly fine for animals like leopard geckos and bearded dragons. Just make sure you’re using something natural and safe. Avoid things like calcium sand, dyed sand, walnut shells, etc. But natural soils/clays/sands, can safely be used.

This statement, is a blanket statement and is simply not true. Loose substrate alone is not going to cause your animal to become impacted. What is? IMPROPER CARE! And I don’t just mean improper substrate, I mean every aspect of the animals care!

Impaction is a word that most reptile owners are familiar with, but there are a LOT of misconceptions out there about it. You often hear that loose substrate leads to impaction (especially in leopard geckos and bearded dragons)
I’ve been getting a LOT of comments on my leopard gecko video telling me that my geckos are going to get impacted, or asking me if I’m worried about impaction. So let’s talk about that!!

I still have a long ways to go, but today I really feel like I had a big breakthrough when it comes to learning about myself and appreciating myself and I wanted to share because I know so many people face the same struggles. You’re all so beautiful ❤️

This is also a reason why I have people saying things like “body positivity promotes obesity”. Body positivity helped me learn how to appreciate myself, it helped me learn how to enjoy exercising, how to enjoy healthy food and overall a healthy life.

Stop putting so much pressure on yourself to change. You don’t need to change. You’ll learn to enjoy things, and enjoy life so much more when you learn how to appreciate and love yourself. Be kind to yourself, and to others.

Exercising and eating healthy feel SO much better when you’re doing it out of love for yourself, rather than out of hate. I’ve struggled with my relationship with food/exercise for a long time and I realized that what I really needed to do all along, was learn how to love myself.

Recently, I realized that this isn’t true. I don’t hate exercising or eating healthy.  I hated myself. Recently I realized that I actually really enjoy things like exercise when I do it to feel strong, and healthy and good about myself.

TW / food/weight.

So many people take breaks, come back and find their channels to be dead basically. It’s so scary to think that I might be risking my channel dying, in order to help fix it.

In order to make these changes, I feel like I need to take a bit of a break and evaluate everything and figure out a plan, however the thought of this is SO scary to me. The YouTube algorithm seems to punish channels who take breaks.

In the new year I really want to focus on putting out quality content that I love and enjoy. But the thought of this is also scary. The thought of making changes, even if they may be beneficial is scary.

All of this reflecting has been good in a way, because it’s made me realize that I want to make changes, but it’s also left me confused, because what do I do now? I know what I want to do - but how do I go about it?

Looking at my analytics confirmed this for me. In my time on YouTube - my views have only gone up and up, but my gained subscribers has gone down. This tells me that people are watching my content - but they’re not finding it entertaining enough to subscribe. https://t.co/PSDiLTSg4M

But upon reflecting, I think that I’ve been slowly killing my channel with that mind set. I was so focused on pumping out videos that I rarely gave myself the time and freedom to create quality content that I was passionate about.

I think in my time being on YouTube, I’ve put so much emphasis on consistency and quantity, that I was lacking quality. I’ve always been proud of myself for being so consistent on YouTube, posting every 3ish days

In the past year, I put out about 100 videos - yet if I look back through them all, very few stand out to me where I think “that was a good video, I’m really proud of it” to me, most of them just seem like very generic content that I’m not particularly happy with.
I love YouTube, I love creating videos and sharing them, but reflecting back on the past year has really made me realize that I’m somewhat disappointed in myself and my channel.

So I filmed a video tonight talking about my feelings with my channel, but idk when that will be posted so I feel like talking about it here as well, so if you’re interested - here is how I’m feeling with my channel.
